1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O d6 {In this chapter, this rare
move will be analyzed. It leads to similar positions like in the Steinitz
variation.} (5... Bd6 $6 {This move defends the e5-pawn and Black's idea is to
castle, play Re8, and retreat the bishop to f8. Black also has the choice to
include the moves b5 and Bb7 at some point.} 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 Bb7 8. Re1 {
White has more than one good option in the position, although this is a very
logical move since ...exd4 will be met with e4-e5.} (8. c3) (8. Bg5 $5) 8...
O-O 9. c3 {White has a very nice center and Black needs to play} h6 {in order
to be able to play Re8 and prevent Ng5.} 10. Nbd2 Re8 {[%cal Gd6f8]} 11. Bc2
Bf8 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black retreats the bishop so that d6 or d5 can become
possible.} 12. Nxe5 {The best way for White to gain an advantage.} Nxe5 13.
dxe5 Rxe5 14. Nf3 {White has ideas of pushing e5.} (14. f4 {This is not very
