5. O-O Nxe4 {This is the Open Spanish.} 6. d4 {All the other moves are
harmless for Black. In this lesson, rare moves for Black will be analyzed.} Be7
$5 {This move was popular around 5-6 years ago. It's a decent line, but if
White knows how to play against it, Black will have some problems.} (6... exd4
$6 {This is an old theory in which White is clearly better.} 7. Re1 d5 (7... f5
$2 8. Nxd4 $18 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 8. Nxd4 Bd6 {Black has the idea to play Bxh2+
and Qh4.} (8... Bc5 $6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. f3 O-O 11. fxe4 dxe4 12. Be3 f5 13.
Nc3 $18 {Black doesn't have enough compensation for the piece, and after 13...
f4, 14.Nxe4 wins on the spot.}) 9. Nxc6 Bxh2+ 10. Kh1 $1 {White is keeping a
close eye on the bishop on h2.} (10. Kxh2 {Leads to a perpetual check.} Qh4+
11. Kg1 Qxf2+ $11) (10. Kf1 $2 Qh4 {Is good for Black.}) 10... Qh4 11. Rxe4+ $1
{The only move.} dxe4 12. Qd8+ {Again, the only move for White.} Qxd8 13. Nxd8+
Kxd8 14. Kxh2 {There is a material imbalance, although White's pieces will
become very active quickly.} Be6 15. Be3 f5 16. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Ge3][%cal
Gc2c3,Gf2f3] White's idea is to play c3 or even f3 in order to open up the
position, while the Black king is still on d8 and can be in danger. White is
clearly better.}) (6... b5 7. Bb3 Be7 (7... exd4 $6 8. Re1 {Perhaps 8.Nxd4 is
also good, but 8.Re1 is better.} d5 9. Nc3 $1 Be6 (9... dxc3 $2 10. Bxd5 $18 {
[%csl Rc6,Re4]}) 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Rxe4 Be7 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Nxd4 $1 {The
best move.} (13. Rxe6 {Is also playable.} Qd7 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Bd2 Bf6 16. Re1
Nd8 17. Re4 $16 {Putting pressure on the d4-pawn and after Black plays 17...c5,
White can reply with 18. Ne5. White has control over the e-file so that puts
White in a much better position.}) 13... O-O (13... Qd5 14. Qg4 $1 O-O-O 15.
Be3 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 $16 {[%csl Re6,Rg7] Black has a lot of weaknesses.}) 14. Bf4
